        article.c-screen.u-clearfix.c-screen--story
            aside.c-screen__sidebar
                h2 The Story
                p As a nonprofit consultant, in the summer of 2013, Ceallaigh Anderson had the privilege of traveling to Rwanda as the logistics coordinator for a leadership speaking team. 
                p While there she was able to travel to small towns and villages, schools, hospitals, churches, a prison, and engage with the rich and the poor, from politicians to the homeless. And one thing was true across the board. Everyone loved to talk with her and have their picture taken. But of course it was the eagerness of the children that had the most impact on her. As soon as she took a picture, each child always wanted to look at the back of her digital camera to see themselves or their family and friends. She desperately wanted to be able to print one out and give it to them! 
                p Thus Love Polaroids was born! Polaroids always spread so much love and smiles. She vowed to be back the following year, ready to print the love.
            img(src='img/story.jpg')

            h4 10 Days in the Land 1000 Hills.<br>1 Encouraging Photographer.<br>1000 Photo Gifts.<br>Life Long Treasures of Love.
            p Ceallaigh travelled back to Rwanda the following year in 2014, during the 20th anniversary of the genocide with camera in tow as she had promised to herself. She raised funds through crowdfunding and brought two Polaroid cameras (Z340 and Z2300) and film. She was able to give away 1,000 Polaroid gifts to people who most likely have never had a printed photo of themselves - a treasure that they will also most likely keep for the rest of their lives. It was a simple small gift to say you matter to each person, child, new mother, or family she encountered. The reactions of the people were incredible! The project was a complete success!
            p None of this would have been possible without you, Polaroid! Thank you!

            h3 Advancing
            p What an amazing gift Ceallaigh got back to be able to witness her vision come alive through the smiles and joy of the Rwandan people as she handed out Polaroids. Many people came forward, even strangers, to support the project to make it happen with their donations and always with such excitement. She wanted to see the vision and passion continue beyond Rwanda. So she began to seek a team of people around her who were passionate about seeing the project grow into an organization where many more people groups can benefit and so others can travel to feel the infectious joy of giving away a Love Polaroids. When thinking through possible funders for continuing this effort it was an obvious and natural choice to approach the Leadership at Polaroid! With both of us great things will happen!

            h3 About the Founder
                span - Ceallaigh Anderson
            p Ceallaigh (pronounced Kelly) has worked in nonprofits for over 15 years in a wide variety of positions and sectors including fundraising, programming, event planning, administration, and now serves as a consultant to many nonprofit organizations in the Twin Cities. As well, she travels often overseas leading teams in various leadership activities. In addition to her consulting, Ceallaigh is a Higher Education advisor and administrator for a world-renowned doctoral leadershi program. With a background and education in Arts Administration (MA) and Experiential/Adventure Education and Art Therapy (BA) Ceallaigh is a perfect leader for Love Polaroids. Ceallaigh is also passionate about running, the arts, the outdoors, fighting for the oppressed, orphan care, organic farming, and is the mother to two future philanthropists.

